<p><b>Francis of Assisi</b> (Giovanni Francesco Bernardone; born <a href="/wiki/1180s" title="1180s">1181/1182</a> – <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="1226-10-03"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="10-03"><a href="/wiki/October_3" title="October 3">October 3</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/1226" title="1226">1226</a></span>)<sup id="cite_ref-cefa_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cefa-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> was a <a href="/wiki/Friar" title="Friar">friar</a> and the founder of the <a href="/wiki/Order_of_Friars_Minor" title="Order of Friars Minor" class="mw-redirect">Order of Friars Minor</a>, more commonly known as the <a href="/wiki/Franciscan" title="Franciscan">Franciscans</a>.</p>
<p>He is known as the <a href="/wiki/Patron_saint" title="Patron saint">patron saint</a> of <a href="/wiki/Animal" title="Animal">animals</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Natural_environment" title="Natural environment">environment</a> and <a href="/wiki/Italy" title="Italy">Italy</a>, and it is customary for <a href="/wiki/Catholic" title="Catholic">Catholic</a> <a href="/wiki/Church_(building)" title="Church (building)">churches</a> to hold ceremonies honoring animals around his <a href="/wiki/Feast_day" title="Feast day" class="mw-redirect">feast day</a> of <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="10-04"><a href="/wiki/October_4" title="October 4">4 October</a></span>.<sup id="cite_ref-dukemag_2-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-dukemag-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<table id="toc" class="toc" summary="Contents">
